{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"766e1f8f-5dc8-400a-bd8e-e33edb6e92fd","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for **Apple's built-in crash reports**:\n\n1. **Crash logs** are written to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS).\n\n2. You can also open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\n3. If you enabled **core dumps** (`ulimit -c unlimited` before running), they land in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n**Key notes:**\n- NativeAOT doesn't ship `createdump` — Apple's crash reporter is your primary source.\n- The `.ips` report includes the faulting thread, stack trace, and signal info.\n- To get symbolicated stacks, keep the `.dsym` bundle (produced by `dotnet publish`) alongside the binary, or use `atos`/`lldb` to symbolicate manually.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"33a2b882-602c-47be-8bb3-6019672fa022","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":301,"requestId":"A040:276D2D:8DE228:B04522:6A0136AF"},"id":"066fc084-26ce-4b8b-81f7-ee3492d2a9b0","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:54:00.642Z","parentId":"0fd57791-7112-4a84-bcb8-059e57832568"}
